item.title: About
item.dc:creator: teturnage
item.content:encoded:
Tallon Reaugh

Web Developer and Designer Student

Web Developer student, anticipated to graduate spring of 2022, who loves to take her imagination and make it digital.

What I Love to do

  • HTML5/ CSS: By creating or redesigning attractive and fully functional websites. This includes elements like text, photos, graphics, animations and videos.
  • Mobile Web Design: Using HTML/CSS and Bootstrap to create responsive web designs. This includes media query, the web browser, and the responsive web interface itself.
  • JavaScript: Implementing complex features on web pages.
  • WordPress: I am able to work with clients to help create, customize, and manage a WordPress site. I have worked with several plugins including; WooCommerce, Yoast SEO, Jetpack CRM, and blogging.

What I have worked with

  • Adobe Cloud: This includes Photoshop, InDesign, and Illustrator. I have used these software's to create a cookbook and design logos.
  • Visual Studio: Configure the HTTP request and response pipeline for a simple ASP.NET Core MVC web app. Used debugging techniques presented to determine the cause of errors and then fixed the errors.
  • PHP: Modify PHP files to implement an Model-View-Controller (MVC) application and testing PHP code.
  • Joomla: This is the newest Content Management System I am currently working with. By the end of this semester I should know how to writing custom components, adapting existing code, and creating my own templates.

By the time I graduate I will be able to use all these languages and tools to create a well-designed and highly functional webpage. For now, I offer services for practice and to add to my portfolio. Contact me for inquiries.

item.title: What to Expect in 2022
item.dc:creator: teturnage
item.content:encoded:
PWA's Will Replace Native Mobile Apps.

New year, new trends! So, what is a PWA, you may ask yourself? PWA stands for progressive web apps. Progressive web apps are web apps that use service workers, manifest, and other web-platform features along with progressive enhancement... come again? This is an app built from the web technologies we all know and love, like HTML, CSS, and JavaScript. All this combine gives the users an experience with native apps. You can build a PWA rather quickly, in regards to a native app that’s pretty difficult to develop. PWAs are not new to the development world, but according to an articles from coredna.com their influence should continue to grow in 2022.

With increase of mobile usage we shall expect the brands to continue with this trend. So, what does this mean for a developer? Beside building two applications, developers should build the website as a PWA for better updated customer experience. After all we are here to make sure the users experience is superior and easy to use.

item.title: Personal
item.dc:creator: teturnage
item.content:encoded:
Have you ever, proudly sat, on a saddle of a 1,500 pound animal? Sitting about 16 hands tall in the air. The bond you feel when you are sitting on this animal is indescribable. You trust them and they trust you. This how I spent many days growing up; at the stables, caring for the horses, and having the incredible opportunity to ride these amazing creatures. I spent about 12 years and then things shifted. Life changed and some changed for the better. Here I am today as a Web Developer Student and a full time mom. Here is a little introduction about who I am. My name is Tallon Reaugh.

Getting To Know Me

Starting From The Top

The first time I sat on an American Quarter Horse, I was eight years old's. My mom and I pulled up to a stable in Laurel Hill, NC called Scotland Saddlebred. We got the honor to meet ole Chip. Chip was about 20 years old at the time. He was the first horse I grew a bond with. After that first ride, there was no going back. I was hooked. I rode until I was 20 years old and showed many times. I took a trip to Southern Pines, NC where I started to learn Hunter Jumping. All these amazing opportunities were beyond a God sent blessing. I truly never thought I would stop riding until I began college. This is all when life took a swift change.

Horse Back Rider To College Girl

I rode my first year of college, but being on my own, for the first time, got in the way with my long time love. I pushed riding to the side for studying and partying. Not knowing how much I would regret it, I had to learn the hard way. I moved several times. From the coastal plains to the city, I traveled around North Carolina looking for a change. I settled in Wilmington, NC for five years. I continued my education and became a waitress, at a downtown restaurant, called Fat Tony's Italian Pub. Life was busy and fast. This next chapter is where I met my best friend aka my husband. This is also the part I met my first love aka my Son.

College Girl to Mom

After not doing what I loved, so much, I just seemed lost on what I wanted to do in life. I was out of mom and dad's house and they were no longer financially supporting me. There was no way I could truly afford equestrian. From time-to-time I would visit Canterbury Stables in Wilmington, NC where one of my old instructors taught at. She would let me ride if I took care of the horses for the morning. Still, I was not sure what to do in life. I already changed my major 4 times in school. One day, God answered my prayers. In 2017, the best thing that had ever happened to me, entered this world. He was a 8 pound 13 ounce fully healthy beautiful baby boy. Two years later we welcomed his little sister into this world. Here I am today happily married, with two beautiful babies, sitting at home typing on this computer as a Web Developer student aiming for new dreams in Raleigh, NC.

Life is truly a beautiful ride.
